The PrintBot Escarabajo is an educational robot that can follow lines, search for light, and grab objects with its claw.
You can see it in action at http://youtu.be/cYbD-ICMmU8
The robot has been designed to attach other components such as servos, LEDs, push buttons, a buzzer, and other sensors included in the product "Mi primer kit de robotica" ("My first robotics kit") distributed by bq.

You will need to print one copy of each part, except for the following:
  • 4 x screw_cover
  • 2 x wheel_front
  • 2 x wheel_rear

    Hardware:

  • 7 x M3x10 screw
  • 1 x M3x12 screw
  • 8 x M3x16 screw
  • 2 x M3x25 screw
  • 2 x M3x35 screw
  • 14 x M3 nut
  • 3 x M3 blocking nut
  • 4 x 3x84mm O-ring
  • 8 x AAA batteries

    Parts included in "Mi primer kit de robotica" by bq:

  • 1 x Freaduino UNO (Arduino UNO derivative)
  • 2 x IR sensors for line following
  • 2 x LDR sensors
  • 2 x Continous Rotation Servo
  • 1 x Miniservo (ES08A / SG90)
  • 1 x 8 AAA battery holder
  • 1 x Bluetooth Module (optional)

    Build Instructions

    See the attached pdf (in Spanish) in the "Files" section. Pictures are clear enough to follow the steps even if you do not understand Spanish.

    Example code

    Attached you will find two simple Arduino programs ("Arduino_escarabajo..."). One follows a line and the other searches for the brightest spot.

    Android-Control

    Now you can control your robot through the "RoboPad" app.
    So just upload the "Arduino_robopad_escarabajo.ino" into your robot, connect the Bluetooth Module and install the Android app:
    https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.bq.robotic.robopad&hl=en
    Youtube trailer: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F8OlUu4fgNo

title: Imagine That Titian/Atlas, Creality CR-10, Afinibot A31 Print Cooling

description.text:
Do you want your part cooling fan to blow the debris off your print bed? Or do you want a strong, flow from at least 2 sides? Do you have a Imagine That Titian/Atlas, Creality CR-10, or Afinibot A31? Well friend, I've got the set-up for you! I didn't use no new fangled CFD programs or nuthin, but I meditated and tried to think like air. Then I over did it. That's even better.

Download the extruder cooling duct here:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2184575
It is nice and compact and raises up the fan away from the heat block.

Additional parts:
2 - 50mmx15mm blowers
2 - M3x20mm socket head bolts (attach the blowers to the bracket/duct)
2 - M3x10mm socket head bolts (attach the bracket to the extruder carrier)
2 - M3 nuts (attach the blowers to the bracket/duct)

Printer Brand:

MakerGear

Printer:

MakerGear M2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.1mm-0.2mm

Infill:

25%-50%

Notes:

Make sure to use a higher temp filament. Scaled for PLA/PETG. Scale up around 2% for ABS. I used Essentium Engineering Grade PLA.

I only had a narrow wall of supports in the middle of the ducts, just a little way in. That way I could still get a pair of needle nose in there to remove them easily.

I printed withe the back, flat part on the bed.
I printed the extruder duct as oriented on the machine, so upright, with the flat down.

description.text:
This is a bracket to mount an nc microswitch sensor on a Wanhao Duplicator 6/Monoprice Maker Ultimate to detect when filament runs out. To be able to use this feature you will need to install a custom Marlin firmware that was developed for the D6/MU:

https://github.com/1bigpig/Marlin

Parts required:

1 nc microswitch similar to that seen in the photo
1 male 3pin JST connector to connect the microswitch to the board
2X m2x12mm screw
2X small sections of PTFE tubing to insert into both ends of the bracket

After installing the firmware, all you need to do is connect an nc microswitch to the board and mount it to the printer using this bracket.

To connect the sensor to the board you'll need a "JST XH 2.5-3 Pin" connector and connect that to the open J9 analog plug on the printer (using the two outermost pins) and connect those wires to the two outermost pins on the microswitch. The printer will automatically detect this once it's plugged in and pause the printer when there is no filament keeping the microswitch closed.

When using rubbing alcohol as a propellant, just swab a little bit of alcohol in the bottle
with a Q-tip. If you are using Butane as a propellant, just hold the valve open for about 3
seconds. Stuff a Q-tip with one end cut off in the barrel as ammo.

description.text:
This is a dual 40mm blower fan mount for the Titan Aero, in a pelvis-like arrangement. Works well, but adding some little nozzles to direct airflow wouldn't hurt.

Note in this picture I am using AE9RB's kossel effector.

I have also updated this with a wider arrangement and fan ducts. Note that you'll want to use ABS, PETG, or something else with a higher melt temp than PLA, otherwise the nozzles may warp.

Notes:

I used PETG to print the one I'm using on my printer, but PLA or ABS should be fine. Honestly, ABS is probably the best choice for weight (but I can't stand the smell).

PLA isn't suitable for the nozzled version, tends to warp.

Required hardware

I used two of the bolts from the Aero kit to attach the mount to the extruder. Depending on the way you're mounting the Aero to your printer, you may need different m3 bolts.

Of course, this also requires two 40mm blower fans, 6x m3x20mm bolts, and 6x m3 nuts.

title: Spinner - with bearings and cap, balanced, no glue

description.text:
Yet another spinner! :)

Everything has been designed for a tight fit with bearings, no glue is necessary (caps also fit snugly). There's no rubbing plastic on plastic for caps, and spinner runs smoothly, quietly and for a long time.

There are two versions available:

  • One with side walls, for more of a triangular look - this one requires supports, as the walls are slightly more narrow than the bearing sockets
  • One without side walls - easier and faster to print, and can be preferred by some (may also be considered easier to spin, since you can push the bearing sockets with your finger)

Here are the bearings I used:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B002BBD6X4/

For smoothest operation, soak the bearings in Isopropyl Alcohol over night, to dissolve the heavy duty grease prior to inserting them into the spinner.

Short video showing it in action:
https://youtu.be/PyDWo5daiDA

And a timelapse showing the print progress:
https://youtu.be/cMRsjPeINFs

For more information, and other interesting projects, please visit my blog:
http://www.BogdanBerg.com/

Enjoy!

Supports are needed for the version with full sides (not the 3-arm simple spinner), as the middle part of the spinner body is slimmer than the bearing sockets (I used grid, and it was quite easy to remove cleanly).

The simpler version doesn't require support.

If for some reason bearing don't fit (based on your printer, settings, etc.) heating up the plastic slightly may help... It's designed for a tight fit, and fits perfectly on the above settings, with PLA, printed on MP Select Mini.

description.text:
A remix of tvputten's tokens designed for dualstrusion printers so you can get a nice crisp contrast between the disc and its number, without painting.  I recommend a white bottom and either black or red tops to match Catan's discs.  
As with tvputten's discs, these lack the letters.  Print as many as you need for either the 3-4 player game, or 5-6 player game, then use a Sharpie to write the letters on the back.  That way you have them for setup but not in the way during play.  You can also use the same tiles for both 3-4 and 5-6 just by having both letters on the back (some tiles will be used only in 5-6 of course).  
I've included the SketchUp files for further remixing.  Note that the import process from tvputten's stl makes a messy SketchUp file, and while I did some cleaning, they're still not as nice as if I had the original source (or had done it from scratch).

Yes, all the "bottom" pieces look the same.  Why the duplication?  To make sure each bottom and its corresponding top line up perfectly when you merge them.  I couldn't easily make sure all the tops were at the exact same starting coordinates, and ReplicatorG gives me no opportunity to align parts when merging (maybe other software does), so this is the surest way to get a good merge.

I removed the holes for attachment to the frame, so you can put it anywhere on the side of your machine, or outside an enclosure, and I moved the hex hole for the left z axis stepper motor cable.

Turns out I made the fan side of the base too high. The fourth screw gets in the way of the X axis motor's travel, so I shrank the bottom's thickness for the next one I print.

I added a version 2 of the bases that have more eyelets for wire management, and have raised stand-offs for the mosfets so you can route wires behind them for more organization.

title: Crosman airgun magazine in 177 caliber - auto index

description.text:
Auto Indexing Magazine designed for Crosman 1377 & CH2009.

  • Clip on to 11mm dovetail
  • Magazine will stop rotating when there's a pellet in the breech. Prevent double loading pellet into the barrel
  • For Auto indexing, just load up to 6 pellet. The unbalanced weight on one side will rotate the magazine automatically.

NOW EVERY SINGLE SHOT AIRGUN BECOMES MULTI-SHOT!!!

Note:

  • I don't own any 22 cal airgun so cannot make 22 cal version sorry.
  • Thanks for the comments of Mr Qyuubi786 and Olddawg. They inspired me to improve the design.

Updates:
Mar 5, 2018

  • Improvements: rotated the rotary pin in the rotary magazine to reduce vertical wiggle.
  • Test printed with eSUN PETG. To see if this material can maintain the tension longer than ABS when biting on to the 11mm dovetail without using a screw. PLA deforms under tension after some time, causing magazine to slide along the dovetail.

A remix of rbuckbailey's harbor pieces designed for dualstrusion printers so you can get a nice crisp contrast between the background and its number, without painting. I recommend a blue bottom and colors to suit the material -- black for wild, red for brick, brown for wood, white for sheep, yellow for wheat, and grey for ore.  
Print as many as you need for either the 3-4 player game, or 5-6 player game.  
I've included the SketchUp files for further remixing. Note that the import process from rbuckbailey's stl makes a messy SketchUp file, and while I did some cleaning, they're still not as nice as if I had the original source (or had done it from scratch).

Yes, all the "bottom" pieces look the same.  Why the duplication?  To make sure each bottom and its corresponding top line up perfectly when you merge them.  I couldn't easily make sure all the tops were at the exact same starting coordinates, and ReplicatorG gives me no opportunity to align parts when merging (maybe other software does), so this is the surest way to get a good merge.

description.text:
Inspired by the nozzle cooler by Zabana.
Because I could only find the one for a single extruder, I decided to design a cooler which will cool both nozzles. Part 1, 2, 3 and 5 can be printed without support.
Part 4 has to be printed with support. First place part 1 and 2 from the back around the extruder block with part 1 on top. (Do this careful around the cable connectors of the stepper motors)
Then insert part 3 from the back until it clicks in place.
Part 4 can be glued on part 3 if necessary.
The cooler is designed for a 60x60mm fan. With a 50x50 fan the airflow is a bit too low.

description.text:
This is a printable linear bearing / bushing. It has the exact same dimensions as a LM8UU (8mm ID, 15mm OD, 24mm length) so it is a drop-in replacement.

I designed this bearing for two reasons: to eliminate the noise created by the generic LM8UU bearings, and to serve as a replacement for the ones that wore out / lost balls.

The design doesn't have any printer-specific tolerances incorporated into it (that is, the inner diameter in the STL is exactly 8mm). When you print it, if you find that the bearing is too loose and that there is noticeable play, then you can scale it down in the X and Y directions. If instead you find that it is too tight (which is more likely to happen), while you could similarly scale it up, I found that the best solution was to run an M8 threaded rod through the bearing. This allows you to smooth out and expand the inner diameter until the bearing slides just right on the smooth rod.

The ideal way to attach the bearing to your printer would be to tightly press it into a mounting block, so that it is under even pressure from all directions. However, simply using zip ties works as well. I used zip ties when attaching these to my current printer, and while this makes the bearings become tighter on the smooth rods, they can still move good enough.

title: CTC/Makerbot Clone Replacement PSU lid for 80mm fans
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A replacement cover and click in fan housing to allow the use of standard 80mm PC fans in the 350w CTC/other makerbot clone power supplies, the fan piece clips in place and is glued afterwards.
I made this quite a tight fit so you may have to shuffle your chosen fan around or make the screw holes larger to give you some wiggle room - I'm using an Arctic F8 PC fan with a resistor to drop the supply to 12v.

Printer:

CTC Bizer Dual

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2-.4

Infill:

2 bottom layers, then 25% fast hex, no top layer required.

Notes:

Print both STL's with the flat surface on the bed, I went with 3 perimeters on a 0.4mm nozzle, 2 bottom layers, 25% hex infill with no top layers (no point, that part is inside anyway, the infill is enough stiffening).
No supports required.

I've since tried another one with a 0.8mm at 0.4mm layer heights with 2 perimeters and prints fine...and much faster.

Works fine in PLA even with the heat generated - it's blowing cold air over itself after all. PET-G would be a better option however.

Post printing - you'll notice the side screw holes aren't printed in the model, mainly because it's much easier to drill them once it's fitted to suit the PSU, or use small self tappers.
If you don't have either of those options then warm the existing screws up and wind them in so they soften the PLA/PET-G and form their own thread.

title: Star Wars Tie Fighter 250 Quad REMIX

description.text:
I have make a full instruction for the build. From the Printing Parts over the equipment, the things you need to buy and the first test flight! And yes, it can fly very well!

You can find it here:

http://www.kopterforum.de/topic/68136-star-wars-tie-fighter-250er-quad-racer/

You need:

12x SPAX 2x10mm
24x SPAX 3x10mm

4x Motor 2205 (2204 is possible, too)
4x ESC without BEC and with min. 20A, better 30A
1x PDB with BEC
1x Flight Controler F3C
1x 4S LiPo Battery
Signal Cable in Black, Red and White
Cable for the Battery and PDB in Black and Red

But you will find a complete List with examples, instructions and the shops you can find all things you need for free here:

http://www.kopterforum.de/topic/68136-star-wars-tie-fighter-250er-quad-racer/

I printed the original TieFighter with the originals .STLs. But I found a lot of Problems and remixed a lot of the .STLs.

Wings:
A few of the Inlets would not the right size, so I change it.

Wings grey:
I sliced this from 2 to 4 Parts with enouth Space for glue.

Motor holder: (Tie Fighter 250er Quad Arm 2204-2205)
I make the hole bigger for the Engine, so the motor can run free.

Motor Mount: (Tie Fighter 250er Quad Motor Mount)
I make a Mount, that you can put betwen the motor and the holder.

LED: (Tie Fighter 250er Quad LED Front)
For the Front Windows I designet a LED Light separation.

Top and Button Cover:
I designet 2 Cover, for the Top and Downside of the main Body. The originial showed a cross, but you never find that in the comics or movies, so I designet it like in "A new Hope".

You can find all .STLs you need at this Remix. So the problem is, that the Engineer from the original Data doesn´t answered on this or other platforms. So you cant find the help from him.

If you need help with this build, pls look at the instruction you can find here: http://www.kopterforum.de/topic/68136-star-wars-tie-fighter-250er-quad-racer/

title: Fidget Spinner Press and bearing remover

description.text:
UPDATE 17DEC2017: I have added a new frame that is larger, "Spinner Press XL". This is to accommodate larger spinners but also because I've found it handy to use the press for other purposes entirely. Also, I have changed the thread pitch of the large screw. It now offers more mechanical advantage and is much easier to turn. I have removed all older designs to clean up the downloads.

I designed this to make it easier to press fit the bearings in to fidget spinners. It presses them in to be perfectly flush.

This works for pressing large ball bearings in to place as well. I tested it with 1/2" ball bearings. You can also use it to remove those bearings.

To use, hand press the bearing in to the spinner a little and then insert in to the press and turn the screw until it's flush. I have found it easier to insert the bearing from the top side of the printed spinner as the bottom tends to flare out a bit on the first layer of printing.

I over engineered this a bit as I wanted to ensure that I wouldn't break it. It's thicker because I didn't want it to bow or bend and I added material around the screw to prevent stripping of the threads.

1 x 608 bearing for main screw
1 x 5mm ID / 10mm OD / 4mm High bearing for removal screw

Printer:

Hatchbox Alpha

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.25mm

Infill:

50%

Notes:

This is over engineered so you probably shouldn't need 50% infill. The standard 20% will probably be fine. I wasn't sure so I did 50% and it's super strong. You'll only print it once so you might as well just print it at 50% so it will last forever.

At 50% infill, it took me 5 hours, 41 minutes to print. 20% infill estimated at 4 hours, 30 minutes. 100% infill was almost 7 hours.

Print the new main screw bearing cap at 100% infill.
Print the new removal screw bearing cap at 100% infill.

DO NOT USE SUPPORTS! Support is unneeded and will cause a lot of issues in the threads

Testing

I tested the deflection (amount of change) when the main screw is tightened as tight as I could turn it and also without any pressure at all.

Not tight: Gap 24.8mm
Tight at 50% infill: Gap 25.1mm
Tight at 20% infill: Gap 25.6mm

So it looks like 20% infill is strong but it allows for a 0.5mm deflection. For the sake of a little longer print and a little more plastic, I'd print at 50% infill and never have to print it again.
